    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Key Takeaway}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        The surface area of the closed cone is given by:
        <me> \pi r^2+ \pi r l</me>

    </p>
    <p>
        Where, where <m>\pi r^2</m> is area of the
        base and <m>\pi r l</m> the area of the curved
        surface. <m>r</m> is the radius of the cone and <m>l</m> is the slant height of the cone.
    </p>
    <p>
        See the figure below.
    </p>
    <image width="50%">
    <latex-image label="A-cone">
        \begin{tikzpicture}[black]
            
            % Cone sector
            \draw[very thick] (0,0) -- (4,3.5) node[midway, above left] {\huge{$l$}};
            \draw[very thick] (0,0) -- (4,-3.5) node[midway, below left] {\huge{$l$}};
            \draw[very thick] (4,3.5) arc[start angle=60, end angle=-60, radius=4];

            % Label for curved surface area
            \draw[very thick,dashed,-&gt;] (3.2,1.5) -- (6,2.5) node[right] {\huge{curved surface}};
            \node[above] at (6.9,2.6){\huge {$A = \pi r l$}};

            % Angle Î¸



            \node at (1.2,0.2) {\huge{$\theta$}};

            % Base circle
            \draw [very thick,fill=cyan](7.5,0) circle (1.5);
            \draw[very thick,dashed,-&gt;] (7.5,0.2) -- (8.5,-2.5) node[right] {\huge{circular base}};
            \node [below]at (10,-2.9) {\huge{$A = \pi r^2$}};

            % Radius of circle
            \draw[very thick,-&gt;] (7.5,0) -- (9,0) ;
            \node [above] at (8.5,0){r};
        \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
        
    </image>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Determine the surface area of the closed cone shown below.
            </p>
            <image width="50%">
            <latex-image label="cone-2">
                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.2]
                    % Base circle (ellipse for 3D effect)
                    \draw[very thick,fill=green] (0,0) ellipse (14 and 4);

                    % Cone sides
                    \draw[very thick] (-14,0) -- (0,25);
                    \draw[very thick] (14,0) -- (0,25);

                    % Dashed line to show radius
                    \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (14,0);
                    \node[below] at (7,0) {14 m};

                    % Slant height
                    \draw[dashed] (0,25) -- (14,0);
                    \node[right] at (7,13) {15 m};
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
                
            </image>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The surface area of the above figure is given by;
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>\text{SA}=\pi r^2 +\pi r l</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Circular base area}=\amp \pi r^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp \frac{22}{7} \times 14 \times 14</mrow>
                   <mrow>= \amp 22 \times 2 \times 14 </mrow>
                   <mrow>= \amp 616 \, \text{m}^2</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Curved surface area}=\amp \pi r l </mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp \frac{22}{7} \times 14 \times 15</mrow>
                   <mrow>= \amp 22 \times 2 \times 15 </mrow>
                   <mrow>= \amp 660\, \text{m}^2</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            
            <p>
                Therefore, the total surface area is given by:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Total surface area} = \amp 616\, \text{m}^2 + 660\, \text{m}^2</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp 1276\, \text{m}^2</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>

        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A conical container open at the top, is made of metal and has a base radius
                of <m>10 \, \text{cm}</m> and a slant height of <m>18 \, \text{cm}</m>. Determine the total metal sheet 
                required to construct this container.
                
            </p>
            
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The conical container has no Circular base therefore, the area is given by:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>\text{Surface area} = \pi r l</m>
               
            </p>
            <p>
                Substitute the given values:
            </p>
            <p>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                 <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Surface area} = \amp \frac{22}{7} \times 10 \times 18</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp \frac{22}{7} \times 180</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp 22 \times 25.714</mrow>
                    <mrow>\approx \amp 565.7\, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore, the total metal sheet required is approximately <m>{\color{blue}565.7\, \text{cm}^2}</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A cone is constructed with a base diameter of <m>20 \, \text{mm}</m> and a height of <m>30 \, \text{mm}</m> as shown below.
            </p>
            <image width="50%">
            <latex-image label="cone-3">
                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.5,rotate=180]
                     % Funnel cone
                    \draw[very thick,fill=white] (0,12) -- (-6,0) -- (6,0) -- cycle;

                    % Elliptical top
                    \draw[very thick, fill=white] (-6,0) arc[start angle=180, end angle=0, x radius=6, y radius=1.2];

                    % Hidden back arc
                    \draw[very thick ,dashed] (6,0) arc[start angle=0, end angle=-180, x radius=6, y radius=1.2];

                    % Labels

                    \node at (-0.5,-0.5) {20 mm};

                    \draw [&lt;-&gt;,very thick] (-6,0) --(-6,12);
                    \node [right]at (-6.3,6) {30 mm};

                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
                
            </image>

            <p>
                <ol marker="a.">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Find the slant height of the cone.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Find the surface area of the cone.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol marker="a.">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The slant height is given by:
                        </p>
                         <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow> l^2= \amp b^2+h^2</mrow>
                                <mrow> l^2 =\amp (\frac{20}{2})+ 30^2</mrow>
                                <mrow>l= \amp \sqrt{10^2+30^2}</mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \sqrt{100 + 900} </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \sqrt{1000} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \approx \amp 31.62\, \text{mm} </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Therefore, the slant height is approximately <m> {\color{blue} 31.62\, \text{mm}}</m>.
                        </p>
                        

                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The total surface area is given by:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\text{TSA} =\amp \pi r^2 + \pi r l </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \pi \times 10^2 + \pi \times 10 \times 31.62 </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \pi \times 100 + \pi \times 316.2 </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp 314.16 + 993.61 </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp 1307.77\, \text{mm}^2 </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Therefore, the total surface area of the cone is approximately <m>{\color{blue}1307.77\, \text{mm}^2}</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <p>
                
            </p>
           
        </solution>
    </example>


    
    
    
